Collecting Twitter Data through Academic API

SICSS-Rutgers 2021

This document provides a brief tutorial on communicating with Twitter Academic API using R’s academictwitteR package. The package is built in May, 2021 by Christopher Barrie and Justin Chun-ting Ho.

To be able to run this code:

  1. You will need to apply for Twitter Academic API, and have an approved developer account for academic research. This link provides information about the application process.

  2. Once your application is approved, you will be able to see your academic project in Twitter’s Developer Portal. You can create a new app or connect an existing app to your project. This will give your bearer token. You can then use your bearer token to connect to Twitter Academic API using R.

  3. You will need the package academictwitteR installed and loaded on your computer.

Getting Started: Installation and Setting Your Bearer Token

Let’s install and/or load the academictwitteR package and some other packages.

## install packages
install.packages("academictwitteR")
install.packages("tidyverse")
## load packages 
library(academictwitteR)
library(tidyverse)

You can also install the developer version of the package from its github page. The developer version allows you to access an introductory vignette.

devtools::install_github("cjbarrie/academictwitteR", build_vignettes = TRUE)
vignette("academictwitteR-intro")

After loading the academictwitteR package, we need to use our bearer token to activate a connection with Twitter’s Academic API. You can find your bearer token in your Developer Portal \(\rightarrow\) Projects and Apps \(\rightarrow\) Your App \(\rightarrow\) Keys and Tokens \(\rightarrow\) Authentication Tokens \(\rightarrow\) Berarer Token.

For identification,the only token you need is your bearer token.

## Assign your bearer token to a character object (you can give any name you want!) 
bearer_token <- "enter your bearer token here"

What can go wrong in here? We need to make sure that we copy and paste our bearer token here as is, without any additional space character.

Main Functions

In this part, we will go over the main functions of the academictwitteR package. Let’s begin!

Search Tweets with Keywords or Hashtags

The workhorse function of the academictwitteR package is the get_all_tweets function. This function allows you to collect tweets containing specific keywords and/or hashtags between specified date ranges, avoiding rate limits by sleeping between calls.

How far can we go back in time and how many tweets can we collect? Academic API allows to have free access to the full history of public conservation, and allows to collect 10,000,000 tweets per month.

While exploring this function, we will also discuss two different ways to store tweets.

1. Data Storage in RDS format, returns a data frame (quick/experimental tasks)

The first way of data storage is to assign our function to an object by specifying a file argument. This will return us a data frame object, and save our data frame as an RDS object in our designated folder (our working directory). Let’s illustrate this with some examples, while exploring this function.

In our first example, we are interested in tweets containing the hashtag #NoWall OR the hashtag #NoBanNoWall. The OR logic allows to collect any tweet that contains either keyword/hashtag. How to use this logic with this function? Putting OR between our keywords/hashtags will result in the OR logic.

## assigining to an object called tweets1,will be a data frame object  
tweets1 <- get_all_tweets(query = "#NoWall OR #NoBanNoWall", 
                              # Any tweet that contains either hashtag 
                 start_tweets = "2018-01-01T00:00:00Z", # start date 
                 end_tweets = "2018-01-05T00:00:00Z", # end date
                 bearer_token = bearer_token, # bearer token to access Twitter API 
                 file = "immigrationtweets1", # name of the resulting RDS file 
                 n= 1000000 # set an upper limit of tweets 
                 # The default limit is set to 200
                 # specificy a file argument - save an RDS format for all the tweets captured with the API call 
                 )

In the second example, we will search tweets containing the sanctuary city keyword OR the hashtag #sanctuarycity. The OR logic again works well for our query. Here, however, we have a keyword, sanctuary city, that we would like to capture as an exact phrase. More specifically, suppose that we don’t want tweets containing words sanctuary and city seperately in our tweets. To match exact phrases in our queries, we need to wrap the phrase in double quotes and use single quotes for the general query.

## assigining to an object called tweets2,will be a data frame object  
tweets2 <- get_all_tweets(query = '"sanctuary city" OR #sanctuarycity', 
                           # Any tweet that contains either keyword/hashtag
                           # wrapping sanctuary city in double quotes, to capture the exact phrase! 
                           start_tweets = "2018-01-01T00:00:00Z", # start date 
                           end_tweets = "2018-01-02T00:00:00Z", # end date
                           bearer_token = bearer_token, # bearer token to access Twitter API 
                           file = "immigrationtweets2", # name of the resulting RDS file 
                           # specificy a file argument - save an RDS format for all the tweets captured with the API call 
                          n= 1000000 # set an upper limit of tweets 
)

What happens if we don’t wrap the phrase sanctuary city in double quotes? If we write "sanctuary city OR #sanctuarycity", then the query will search for tweets containing the words sanctuary AND city OR the hashtag #sanctuarycity. You can see the difference from the previous query by running the code chunk below.

## assigining to an object called tweets_2,will be a data frame object  
tweets2_diff <- get_all_tweets(query = "sanctuary city OR #sanctuarycity", 
                          # Any tweet that contains either keyword/hashtag
                           # wrapping sanctuary city in double quotes, matches the exact phrase! 
                           start_tweets = "2018-01-01T00:00:00Z", # start date 
                           end_tweets = "2018-01-02T00:00:00Z", # end date
                           bearer_token = bearer_token, # bearer token to access Twitter API 
                           file = "immigrationtweets2_diff", # name of the resulting RDS file 
                            #specificy a file argument - save an RDS format for all the tweets captured with the API call 
                           n= 1000000 # set an upper limit of tweets
                          )

tweets3 <- get_all_tweets(query = '"sanctuary city" Chicago',

When to use this data storage? This works well if we want to try out something for a short time period, or if we want to experiment with query building.

Now, we will move on with the second way of data stroge. This will be more appropriate if our aim is to collect a larger set of tweets.

2. Storage in JSON files with a data path (larger tasks)

Let’s say we are interested in tweets about immigration with the key word sanctuary city OR the hashtag #sanctuarycity over a long time period, say 10 years. This API call will run at least several days by paginating over each Twitter page that match our query! For such tasks, the package suggests to store the data as a series of JSON files to mitigate data loss. In practice, we just need to modify our previous code chunks a little bit. We will add two additional arguments to the get_all_tweets function: 1) name our data directory where we want to save our data using the data_path argument, 2) don’t bind the tweets in a single data frame by setting bind_tweets argument to FALSE. This is because our data will be stored in multiple JSON files in a folder. Each file will contain approximately up to 500 tweets. We will also remove the file argument we had before. Lastly, we will not assign the function to any object since the function won’t return anything here! Let’s illusrate with an example.

get_all_tweets(query = '"sanctuary city" OR #sanctuarycity', 
               # Any tweet that contains either key word/hashtag
               # wrapping sanctuary city in double quotes, matches the exact phrase! 
               start_tweets = "2018-01-01T00:00:00Z", # start date 
               end_tweets = "2018-01-02T00:00:00Z", # end date
               bearer_token = bearer_token, # bearer token to access Twitter API 
               data_path = "immigration_tweets/", # data path where JSON files will be stored 
               bind_tweets = FALSE, # don't bind the tweets
               n= 1000000 # set an upper limit of tweets 
)
## query: <"sanctuary city" OR #sanctuarycity>: (tweets captured this page: 493). Total pages queried: 1. Total tweets ingested: 493. 
## query: <"sanctuary city" OR #sanctuarycity>: (tweets captured this page: 23). Total pages queried: 2. Total tweets ingested: 516. 
## This is the last page for "sanctuary city" OR #sanctuarycity : finishing collection.
## Data stored as JSONs: use bind_tweets function to bundle into data.frame

The collected tweets are now in our data path in the folder immigration_tweets as multiple JSON files. Let’s check how many JSON files we have.

## can check the files included
list.files("immigration_tweets") # total 4 json files and one query text file

## [3] "data_947630920458268673.json"  "query"                        
## [5] "users_.json"                   "users_947618995229753346.json"
## [7] "users_947630920458268673.json"

How to bind our tweets that are stored in multiple JSON files? We need to find a way to convert these JSON files into a format that we can use for our analysis. Good news! There is a very convenient function to do this. We can use a function called bind_tweets. This function will return us a data frame.

immig_data <- bind_tweets(data_path = "immigration_tweets")
## ================================================================================

Now, we have a data frame.

Collect User Tweets

To collect tweets of a user or set of users between specified date ranges we can use the function get_user_tweets. Let’s collect tweets of some U.S. governors between March, 2021 and June, 2021.

To make our life easier, we can assign multiple users we are interested in to an object called users.

## assign an object to accounts you are interested in 
users <- c("GavinNewsom", "GovWhitmer", "GovLauraKelly", "OregonGovBrown")
get_user_tweets(users, # users object 
               start_tweets = "2021-03-01T00:00:00Z", # start date
               end_tweets = "2021-05-01T00:00:00Z", # end date
               bearer_token = bearer_token, # bearer token 
               data_path = "governors_tweets/", # data path where JSON files will be stored 
               bind_tweets = FALSE,# don't bind the tweets
               n= 1000000 # set an upper limit of tweets 
               ) 
## query: <(from:GavinNewsom OR from:GovWhitmer OR from:GovLauraKelly OR from:OregonGovBrown)>: (tweets captured this page: 500). Total pages queried: 1. Total tweets ingested: 500. 
## query: <(from:GavinNewsom OR from:GovWhitmer OR from:GovLauraKelly OR from:OregonGovBrown)>: (tweets captured this page: 380). Total pages queried: 2. Total tweets ingested: 880. 
## This is the last page for (from:GavinNewsom OR from:GovWhitmer OR from:GovLauraKelly OR from:OregonGovBrown) : finishing collection.
## Data stored as JSONs: use bind_tweets function to bundle into data.frame

These tweets are now in our data path as multiple JSON files in the folder governors_tweets. Let’s bind these JSON files.

We can figure out which author ID belongs to which governor. But, there is an easier way to retrieve governor names. We can use the get_user_profile() function to retrieve the user profiles.

## assign an object to retrieve and store author ids
authors <- gov_data$author_id
## use this obect to get user profiles by activating your bearer token 
authors_profile <- get_user_profile(authors, bearer_token)

If we are only interested in names of the governors, we can subset the name column from our users profile data frame. We can then add this as a column to our original governors data frame.

authors_profile2 <- authors_profile %>% select(name)
gov_data <- cbind(gov_data, authors_profile2)
table(gov_data$name)

In the academictwitteR package, currently, there is no build-in function like ts_plot (rtweet package) for plotting tweets as a time series graph. But, we can use ggplot!

## we already loaded tidyverse (includes ggplot2)
# first, need to convert the created_at variable, this format is not appropriate for plotting
head(gov_data$created_at)
## [1] "2021-03-25T15:42:57.000Z" "2021-03-25T15:39:26.000Z"
## [3] "2021-03-25T15:11:32.000Z" "2021-03-25T15:09:30.000Z"
## [5] "2021-03-25T02:53:11.000Z" "2021-03-25T02:51:13.000Z"
## let's name our new variable date
## there are many different ways to do this conversion
gov_data$date <- as.Date(gov_data$created_at)
head(gov_data$date)
## [1] "2021-03-25" "2021-03-25" "2021-03-25" "2021-03-25" "2021-03-25"
## [6] "2021-03-25"
## Now we need to collapse the tweets at the day level for each governor 
dat_collapsed_daily <- gov_data %>% group_by(name, date) %>% summarize(n())
dat_collapsed_daily <- dat_collapsed_daily %>% mutate(frequency = `n()`)
## time to plot our tweets 
dat_collapsed_daily %>% 
  # line below, core component of our plot: `data` and `mapping`. 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = frequency, group = name, color = name)) + geom_line() +  
  # positin new scales for date on the x-axis  
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "15 days", date_labels = "%b-%d-%y") +
  # give a title 
  ggtitle("Tweet Frequency from Four Governors",subtitle = "tweet counts aggregated daily") +
  # change the name of the legend
  labs(color='Governors') +
  # change legend labels/colors
  scale_color_manual(labels = c("Newsom", "Whitmer", "Brown", "Kelly"), values = c("aquamarine3", "red", "orange",
  "purple")) + 
  # change the names of x and y axis labels

Getting Videos and Images

Functions get_video_tweets and get_image_tweets allow to collect tweets with videos or images for specific keywords and hashtags between specified date ranges.

tweets with videos contain native Twitter videos, uploaded directly to Twitter. The function do not match videos created with other applications such as Periscope, or tweets with links to other video hosting sites. Below is an example for videos containing the hashtag #BlackLivesMatter. This time, let’s use the first way of storing tweets.

Filtering Tweets by Location

There are two types of geographical metadata when we are collecting Twitter data.

1. Tweet location: Available when user shares location at time of tweet.

2. Account Location: Based on the ‘home’ location provided by user in their public profile. This is a
free-form character field and may or may not contain metadata that can be geo-referenced. These are described separately in the next two sections.

This link and this link provides more information for filtering tweets by location. We will discuss some examples for collecting Twitter data by tweet location in the next part on building queries.

Building Queries

Manual Queries

Twitter Academic API can accept fairly complex queries (a query can be 1024 characters long!). This link provides a detailed overview of building queries with some examples.

Suppose that we are interested in tweets containing the hashtag #BlackLivesMatter from a specific country, United States, that are only English. We also want to exclude retweets. For collecting tweets by country, we can use the place_country operator.

blm_query1 <- get_all_tweets("#BlackLivesMatter place_country:US lang:en -is:retweet",
                             start_tweets = "2020-01-01T00:00:00Z",
                             end_tweets = "2020-02-01T00:00:00Z",
                             bearer_token,
                             n= 1000000 # set an upper limit of tweets 
                             )
## query: <#BlackLivesMatter place_country:US lang:en -is:retweet>: (tweets captured this page: 347). Total pages queried: 1. Total tweets ingested: 347. 
## This is the last page for #BlackLivesMatter place_country:US lang:en -is:retweet : finishing collection.

Now, our columns related to geographical metadata is not empty anymore. But, unfortunately, we are now getting way less tweets than we would have without the location.

We can also use an operator called bounding box. This allows to specify a 4-sided geographic area and match tweets containing tweet-specific location data that fall within that area. Let’s say we are interested in collecting tweets with the hastag #BlackLivesMatter in the Bronx area.

Bronx, Bounding Box

## bounding_box:[west_long south_lat east_long north_lat]
# -73.9393484455,40.785171272,-73.8185225894,40.9007276281
## each side of the box is up to 25 miles in length.
blm_query3 <- get_all_tweets("#BlackLivesMatter bounding_box:[-73.93 40.78 -73.82 40.90] lang:en", 
                             start_tweets = "2020-01-01T00:00:00Z",
                             end_tweets = "2020-01-05T00:00:00Z",
                             bearer_token,
                             n= 1000000 # set an upper limit
)
## Rate limit reached, sleeping... 
## query: <#BlackLivesMatter bounding_box:[-73.93 40.78 -73.82 40.90] lang:en>: (tweets captured this page: 4). Total pages queried: 1. Total tweets ingested: 4. 
## This is the last page for #BlackLivesMatter bounding_box:[-73.93 40.78 -73.82 40.90] lang:en : finishing collection.

Another operator for collecting tweets by location is the point_radius operator. This allows to specify a circular geographic area and match tweets containing tweet-specific location data that fall within that area. For example, we can look at the tweets containing the keyword insurrection in a 25 miles radius around the Capitol on January 6, 2021.

Capitol, Radius

## point_radius:[lon lat radius]
## radius must be less than 25 miles! 
capitol_radius <- get_all_tweets("insurrection point_radius:[-77.009017 38.890550 25mi]",

                                 end_tweets = "2021-01-07T00:00:00Z",
                                 bearer_token,
                                 n= 1000000 # set an upper limit of tweets 
)

Query Builder

Manual approach requires to know the syntax of Twitter API queries. Alternatively, we can benefit from the academictwitteR package’s own query builder, build_query function.

We can build tweet queries according to the following parameters.

args(build_query)
## function (query = NULL, users = NULL, reply_to = NULL, retweets_of = NULL, 
##     exclude = NULL, is_retweet = NULL, is_reply = NULL, is_quote = NULL, 
##     is_verified = NULL, remove_promoted = FALSE, has_hashtags = NULL, 
##     has_cashtags = NULL, has_links = NULL, has_mentions = NULL, 
##     has_media = NULL, has_images = NULL, has_videos = NULL, has_geo = NULL, 
##     place = NULL, country = NULL, point_radius = NULL, bbox = NULL, 
##     lang = NULL, conversation_id = NULL, url = NULL) 
## NULL

The example below shows how to build a query to collect tweets containing the #BlackLivesMatter hashtag by country. This function will build us a tweet query. We will then use this as an input in the function get_all_tweets as query parameter.

blm_querybuild <- build_query(query = "#BlackLivesMatter", country = "US", lang = "en")
blm_querybuild
## [1] "#BlackLivesMatter place_country:US lang:en"
blmquery_tweets <- get_all_tweets(blm_querybuild, # insert query parameter from the build quey function 
                             start_tweets = "2020-01-01T00:00:00Z",
                             end_tweets = "2020-03-01T00:00:00Z",
                             bearer_token,
                             n= 1000000 # set an upper limit of tweets of one million
                             )
## query: <#BlackLivesMatter place_country:US lang:en>: (tweets captured this page: 497). Total pages queried: 1. Total tweets ingested: 497. 
## query: <#BlackLivesMatter place_country:US lang:en>: (tweets captured this page: 424). Total pages queried: 2. Total tweets ingested: 921. 
## This is the last page for #BlackLivesMatter place_country:US lang:en : finishing collection.

Interruption and Continuation

When making long API calls, there might be some interruptions. resume_collection function resumes a previous interrupted collection session. Because we don’t experienced any interruption while collecting immigration tweets, the function won’t give us any new tweets.

resume_collection(data_path = "immigration_tweets", bearer_token)
## ================================================================================

## data frame with 0 columns and 0 rows

Some Updates

The updates below provide sample code for some common questions asked after the tutorial. 1. How to collect tweets containing keywords/hashtags from some specific users? 2. How to get more fields (columns) when making a query by using the fields or expansions parameters?

How to Collect Tweets containing keywords/hashtags from some specific users?

Let’s collect some covid related keywords from some governors! You can the get_all_tweets function by building a query that feeds both the keywords and user names as inputs into the function. This function returns tweets containing keywords not only in the main text of tweets but also in the embedded urls. It also collect tweets by capturing keywords as stand-alone words. For example, it won’t return a tweet that includes the hashtag #covidishere. Lastly, when we are using the Academic API, our query can be 1024 characters long.

covid_dat <- get_all_tweets(
  query = c("mask", "covid"),
  users = c("GavinNewsom", "GovWhitmer", "OregonGovBrown"),
  start_tweets = "2020-01-01T00:00:00Z",
  end_tweets = "2021-01-01T00:00:00Z",
  bearer_token,
  n = 1000000
)
## query: <(mask OR covid) (from:GavinNewsom OR from:GovWhitmer OR from:OregonGovBrown)>: (tweets captured this page: 499). Total pages queried: 1. Total tweets ingested: 499. 
## query: <(mask OR covid) (from:GavinNewsom OR from:GovWhitmer OR from:OregonGovBrown)>: (tweets captured this page: 294). Total pages queried: 2. Total tweets ingested: 793. 
## This is the last page for (mask OR covid) (from:GavinNewsom OR from:GovWhitmer OR from:OregonGovBrown) : finishing collection.

You can also write this like below, consistent with Twitter’s query building.

covid_dat_alt <- get_all_tweets(
  '(mask OR covid) (from:GavinNewsom OR from:GovWhitmer OR from:OregonGovBrown)',
  start_tweets = "2020-01-01T00:00:00Z",
  end_tweets = "2021-01-01T00:00:00Z",
  bearer_token,
  n= 1000000) 
## query: <(mask OR covid) (from:GavinNewsom OR from:GovWhitmer OR from:OregonGovBrown)>: (tweets captured this page: 499). Total pages queried: 1. Total tweets ingested: 499.

How to get more fields (columns) when making a query by using the fields or expansions parameters?

By default, the Twitter Academic API data objects deliver a small number of default fields: 14 fields/columns. To get more fields, first, we can use the get_user_profile() function provided by the academictwitteR function. Second, we can use Twitter’s fields or expansions query parameters. For the latter, we could try to manually unnest some nested fields. In the next versions of the package, it is highly likely that the package might allow to incorporate different fields!

This link and this link provide further information about the logic of fields and expansions.

By default, the function returns 15 fields.

## rename the data frame 
covid2_dat <- covid_dat
names(covid2_dat)
##  [1] "id"                  "author_id"           "conversation_id"    
##  [4] "possibly_sensitive"  "source"              "context_annotations"
##  [7] "entities"            "public_metrics"      "created_at"         
## [10] "text"                "lang"                "referenced_tweets"  
## [13] "in_reply_to_user_id" "attachments"         "withheld"

Here is some brief explanation about the returned fields

  • attachments: Specifies the type of attachments (if any) present in this Tweet, e.g. media keys
  • public_metrics: Public engagement metrics for the Tweet at the time of the request, e.g. retweet count, reply count, like count, quote count. You can use this to measure engagement.
  • conversation_id: The Tweet ID of the original Tweet of the conversation (which includes direct replies, replies of replies).
  • source: The name of the app the user Tweeted from.
  • context_annotations: Contains context annotations for the Tweet, e.g. domain, id, name, description
  • author_id: The unique identifier of the User who posted this Tweet.
  • possibly_sensitive: The meaning of the field doesn’t pertain to the Tweet content itself, but instead it is an indicator that the URL contained in the Tweet may contain content or media identified as sensitive content.
  • created_at: Creation time of the Tweet.
  • lang: Language of the Tweet, if detected by Twitter.
  • entities: Entities which have been parsed out of the text of the Tweet. These are JSON objects that provide additional information about hashtags, urls, user mentions, and cashtags associated with a Tweet.
  • text: The actual UTF-8 text of the Tweet.
  • id: The unique identifier of the requested Tweet.
  • referenced_tweets: A list of Tweets this Tweet refers to, e.g. if the parent Tweet is a Retweet, a Retweet with comment (also known as Quoted Tweet) or a Reply, it will include the related Tweet referenced to by its parent.
  • in_reply_to_user_id: If the represented Tweet is a reply, this field will contain the original Tweet’s author ID.
  • withheld: When present, indicates whether the content being withheld.

Source: Twitter

Currently, we only see major fields returned by the function. However, there are many more fields that are nested within these fields! Here is an illustration from the referenced_tweets field:

For example, public metrics is a data frame, referenced_tweets is a list and so on. We need to find a way to put these subfields out of this nest (unnest)!

Using the get_user_profile() function

First, we can use the get_user_profile() function to retrieve some additional fields related to user profiles without manually nesting the fields. Let’s check which additional fields we can get by using this function.

## assign an object to retrieve and store author ids
authors2 <- covid2_dat$author_id
## use this obect to get user profiles by activating your bearer token 
authors2_profile <- get_user_profile(authors2, bearer_token)
## Processing from 1 to 100
## Processing from 101 to 200
## Processing from 201 to 300
## Processing from 301 to 400
## Processing from 401 to 500
## Processing from 501 to 600
## Processing from 601 to 700
## Processing from 701 to 793

Let’s check the columns returned by this function.

names(authors2_profile)
##  [1] "protected"         "url"               "profile_image_url"
##  [4] "location"          "name"              "entities"         
##  [7] "description"       "id"                "username"         
## [10] "created_at"        "public_metrics"    "verified"

For example, previously, we didn’t have fields such as username, name, description, protected, verified, profile_image_url, location, url etc. These are some unnested fields by the function, e.g. name, description are unnested from context_annotations.

We can extend our fields by adding these new fields to our data frame.

authors2_profile_add <- authors2_profile %>% select(username, name, description, protected, verified, profile_image_url, location, url)
covid2_dat_new <- cbind(covid2_dat, authors2_profile_add)
names(covid2_dat_new)
##  [1] "id"                  "author_id"           "conversation_id"    
##  [4] "possibly_sensitive"  "source"              "context_annotations"
##  [7] "entities"            "public_metrics"      "created_at"         
## [10] "text"                "lang"                "referenced_tweets"  
## [13] "in_reply_to_user_id" "attachments"         "withheld"           
## [16] "username"            "name"                "description"        
## [19] "protected"           "verified"            "profile_image_url"  
## [22] "location"            "url"

Unnesting Fields Manually

Second, we can manually unnest some fields ourselves. Here, we can have more control over the customization of the fields. We will use different methods to unnest the fields depending on their classes.

## install packages
install.packages("tidyr")
install.packages("purrr")
## load packages 
library(tidyr)
library(purrr)

To illusrate, let’s unnest the public_metrics which is a data frame.

class(covid2_dat$public_metrics)
## [1] "data.frame"
head(covid2_dat$public_metrics)
##   retweet_count reply_count like_count quote_count
## 1            72         253        434          15
## 2            48           0          0           0
## 3           128         273       1103          40
## 4            57          52        751           6
## 5            52          12        427          10
## 6            36         294        239           8

We can use cbind to combine our original data frame and the public metrics data frame.

covid2_dat_unnested <- cbind(covid2_dat, covid2_dat$public_metrics) %>% 
  select(-public_metrics) # remove public_metrics to avoid duplicates, we unnested it!

We can do the same for other fields that are data frames such as entities and attachments.

covid2_dat_unnested <- cbind(covid2_dat_unnested, covid2_dat$attachments, covid2_dat$entities) %>% 
  select(-attachments, -entities) # remove the original fields, we unnested it!

Let’s check the columns of our original data frame again. It has now 29 fields!

names(covid2_dat_unnested)
##  [1] "id"                  "author_id"           "conversation_id"    
##  [4] "possibly_sensitive"  "source"              "context_annotations"
##  [7] "created_at"          "text"                "lang"               
## [10] "referenced_tweets"   "in_reply_to_user_id" "withheld"           
## [13] "retweet_count"       "reply_count"         "like_count"         
## [16] "quote_count"         "media_keys"          "urls"               
## [19] "mentions"            "annotations"         "hashtags"

What about the fields that are lists? We need to tackle them differently.

# lapply(covid2_dat_unnested, class)

Let’s illustrate how to unnest the lists focusing on referenced_tweets.

class(covid2_dat_unnested$referenced_tweets)
## [1] "list"

We will use a function called unnest_wider for collapsing nested lists into columns.

covid2_dat_unnested <- covid2_dat_unnested %>% 
  unnest_wider(referenced_tweets, names_repair = "unique")
## one of the fields of referenced_tweets is id, we have id in our original data frame, that's why we 
## need to set it to unique

Now, we have three new columns: - id…3 is the referenced id (class: character) - id…11 is the referenced tweet (class: list) - type is the referenced type (class: list)

Let’s give an informative name to the referenced id field.

names(covid2_dat_unnested)[names(covid2_dat_unnested) == "id...3"] <- "ref_id"

We need to further unnest the lists. Referenced tweets refer to multiple things, e.g. replied tweets, quoted tweets, and retweeted tweets. It seems like some tweets are both replied and quoted tweets. That’s why we end up having a list again.

covid2_dat_unnested <- covid2_dat_unnested %>% 
  unnest_wider(id...11)

Let’s give informative names to the two columns for the referenced tweets fields.

names(covid2_dat_unnested)[names(covid2_dat_unnested) == "...1"] <- "ref_tweets1"
names(covid2_dat_unnested)[names(covid2_dat_unnested) == "...2"] <- "ref_tweets2"

The same applies to the type field.

covid2_dat_unnested <- covid2_dat_unnested %>% 
  unnest_wider(type, names_repair = "unique")
## one of the fields of referenced_tweets is type, we have type in our original data frame, that's why we 
## need to set it to unique

Now, let’s give some informative names to our newly added columns for the field type.

names(covid2_dat_unnested)[names(covid2_dat_unnested) == "...10"] <- "ref_type1"
names(covid2_dat_unnested)[names(covid2_dat_unnested) == "...11"] <- "ref_type2"

Now, we unnested the list for the referenced_tweets column! You can do the same for the other columns that are lists.

names(covid2_dat_unnested)
##  [1] "id"                  "author_id"           "conversation_id"    
##  [4] "possibly_sensitive"  "source"              "context_annotations"
##  [7] "created_at"          "text"                "lang"               
## [10] "ref_type1"           "ref_type2"           "ref_tweets1"        
## [13] "ref_tweets2"         "in_reply_to_user_id" "withheld"           
## [16] "retweet_count"       "reply_count"         "like_count"         
## [19] "quote_count"         "media_keys"          "urls"               
## [22] "mentions"            "annotations"         "hashtags"

    • get_to_tweets: collects tweets between specified date ranges that are in reply to the specified user(s)
    • get_country_tweets: collects tweets containing specific keywords and hashtags between specified date ranges filtering by country.
    • get_geo_tweets: collects tweets containing specific keywords and hashtags between specified date ranges that also contain tweet-specific geolocation data provided by the Twitter user.
    • get_lang_tweets: collects tweets containing specific keywords and hashtags between specified date ranges by language.
    • get_mention_tweets: collects tweets containing specific keywords and hashtags between specified date ranges that also contain mentions of other Twitter users.
